data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes `Func<>`, not `Expression<Func<>>`

Your expression-tree construction **won't compile** because the new overload accepts a plain lambda. Replace the entire block:

```csharp
// EF Core 10 — no expression trees needed
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

---

### 2. Complex type column names — now uniquified & nested paths change

Two sub-changes:

- **Duplicate names get a numeric suffix.** Both `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously silently shared one `Street` column — now they'll get `Street` and `Street1`.
- **Nested complex types use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was `BillingAddress_City`, now becomes `Payment_BillingAddress_City`.

**This will generate a migration that renames columns**, breaking your existing database unless you pin the old names:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));   // keep shared column
});

// For nested complex types, pin old column names:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");   // was the old default
```

> ⚠️ Only pin the old names if you want to preserve your existing schema. If you're OK with the rename, just generate and apply a new migration.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on the interface now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (for redacted SQL logging). Your class won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)          // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
